---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I need a planning permit from Casey Council for a backyard pool?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A building permit is required for every pool over 300mm deep — that is universal. A separate planning permit is only required if the property sits in a Significant Landscape Overlay, Heritage Overlay, Bushfire Management Overlay, Vegetation Protection Overlay, or if the pool encroaches setback rules. About 15–20% of Berwick blocks are in an overlay that triggers a planning-permit requirement, mostly in older heritage parts and the rural-residential fringes. We check the overlay status using the Planning Property Report on the first site visit before lodging anything — adds two days, saves potential weeks of refusal." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How does neighbour notification actually work, and can a neighbour object?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "For most pool builds the only notification required is the Building Permit notice posted to the boundary, and notice given to adjoining owners under Section 84 of the Building Act 1993 only if your build affects their land — for example if excavation is within 1.5m of a shared boundary, or if you need to remove and reinstate a section of fence. A planning permit triggers a public notice period (typically 14 days) during which any party can object. Casey Council manages the process. The pre-build conversation we have with you is: identify the neighbours whose lives the build will touch (noise, dust, truck movements, fence access) and have a one-page heads-up letter delivered before the dig starts. It costs nothing and resolves 90% of friction." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much soil actually comes out, and where does it go?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A standard 8m × 4m pool with a 1.2–1.85m depth profile generates 55–75 cubic metres of spoil — that is 5 to 7 truck loads of an 11m³ tipper, or 8 to 10 loads of a 7m³ smaller tipper. On Casey reactive clay the spoil cannot go back as backfill (it would re-swell and lift the shell), so 100% of it leaves site. Clean clay goes to construction-fill recipients (often free or low-cost tipping); contaminated or rocky spoil goes to a licensed transfer station ($60–$90 per cubic metre). We organise the disposal and include it in the fixed quote — there is no ‘oh by the way the dump fees were more than expected’ variation from us." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the access-easement issue and why does it matter?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Many Berwick blocks — particularly the deeper rural-residential ones around the Berwick-Cranbourne border — have registered easements running across the backyard. Stormwater easements, sewer easements, electricity-supply easements, telecommunications easements. You cannot build over an easement and you cannot excavate within the protective zone without the asset-owner’s written consent. Yarra Valley Water (sewer), South East Water (water main) and South East Power (electricity) each have a build-over application process taking 3–8 weeks. We pull a title and a Section 32 Vendor’s Statement on the first visit, identify any easements, and either redesign the pool footprint to clear them or lodge the build-over application immediately. Discovering an easement halfway through excavation is the worst case." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Five-truck-and-excavator vs mini-excavator — which is right for my block?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "It depends entirely on access. A standard 8-ton excavator with 5-truck tipper turnaround can dig and remove a pool-sized hole in 1–2 days — fast, efficient, and the cheapest option per cubic metre. It needs 3.5m of clear side-access width, a stable driveway, and room to turn. About 60% of Berwick blocks have that. For tighter blocks — older Endeavour Hills, narrow-frontage Hampton Park, anything with a single-car driveway and overhead wires — we use a 1.7-ton mini-excavator that fits through a 1.2m gate. Dig takes 4–6 days instead of 1–2, and the cost is $4,000–$8,000 higher because of the slower production rate. The alternative is removing fence panels, which is sometimes cheaper than the upgrade — we work that out at the site visit." }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
