  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>The Casey Council pre-build process.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          Every pool over 300mm deep needs a building permit from a registered
          building surveyor, full stop. That is regulated under the Building Act
          1993 and the Building Regulations 2018, not Casey Council directly —
          Council is involved through the planning system and through the asset
          owner role on stormwater and drainage. The order of operations matters
          and the wrong sequence can add 4–6 weeks to a build.
        </p>
        <p>
          Step one: pull the Planning Property Report from the State Government’s
          Vicplan portal. This tells you the zone, every overlay that applies to
          the block, and the bushfire and heritage status. Most of Berwick is
          General Residential Zone with no special overlay — clean and quick.
          Some pockets — heritage parts of Old Berwick, the rural-residential
          fringes toward Beaconsfield Upper, and Bushfire Management Overlay
          parcels in the hills — trigger a planning permit before the building
          permit can be issued.
        </p>
        <p>
          Step two: pull a current copy of title and the Section 32 Vendor’s
          Statement. This is where registered easements show up. Stormwater
          easements, sewer easements, electricity supply easements,
          telecommunications easements. You cannot build over an easement without
          the asset owner’s written consent, and excavation within the protective
          zone (typically 1.0–1.5m from the centreline) requires the same
          approval.
        </p>
        <p>
          Step three: lodge the build-over applications if any easement is in
          play. Yarra Valley Water (sewer), South East Water (water and
          recycled-water mains), South East Power (electricity), and NBN
          (telecommunications) each have their own process. Typical turnaround:
          3–8 weeks. We lodge in week one so the approval lands before
          excavation needs to start.
        </p>
        <p>
          Step four: building surveyor lodges the building permit. Soil report,
          structural engineering, AS 1926 pool fence design, AS 2783 excavation
          design, and AS 1839 shotcrete shell design all need to be in the
          submission. Standard turnaround 5–10 working days for a complete
          submission.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Neighbour notification — formal and informal.</h3>
        <p>
          The formal notification is light. The Building Permit is publicly
          noticed by being posted on the property boundary visible from the
          street. Section 84 of the Building Act requires written notice to
          adjoining property owners only if the construction will affect their
          land — for example, excavation within 1.5m of a shared boundary, or
          temporary removal of a shared fence. A planning permit (when required)
          triggers a 14-day public notice period during which any party can
          object.
        </p>
        <p>
          The informal notification is where the relationship is actually built.
          Two weeks before the dig, we recommend handing a one-page letter to
          every direct neighbour: dates, hours, expected truck movements, the
          name and mobile of our site supervisor, and a thank-you-in-advance for
          their patience. Costs nothing, takes 30 minutes, and resolves
          everything from disputes about parking to angry phone calls about
          dust. We can draft this letter for you — we do it for most builds.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">The soil-haul calculation.</h3>
        <p>
          A standard 8m × 4m pool with a 1.2m shallow end and a 1.85m deep end
          generates about 65 cubic metres of spoil, including the over-dig
          allowance for piers and working clearance. On reactive Casey clay,
          none of that spoil can go back into the hole as backfill — it would
          re-swell and lift the shell. So 100% leaves site, in 5–7 loads of an
          11m³ tipper truck or 8–10 loads of a 7m³ smaller tipper.
        </p>
        <p>
          Where the spoil goes depends on what it is. Clean uncontaminated clay
          is the easiest — local construction-fill projects often take it for
          free or a small fee. Wet, rocky, or organic-laden spoil goes to a
          licensed transfer station at $60–$90 per cubic metre. Spoil that has
          tested above contamination thresholds (rare in Berwick but possible
          near former industrial parcels) goes to a Category C cell at $140+
          per cubic metre.
        </p>
        <p>
          We include the disposal in the fixed quote — based on a clay-haul
          assumption confirmed by the soil report. If contamination shows up
          during the dig that we could not have anticipated, that becomes a
          variation; otherwise the haul cost is locked in at contract.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">The excavator decision.</h3>
        <p>
          One of the biggest hidden cost drivers on a pool build is the
          excavator choice, which is driven entirely by access. Three scenarios
          we see across Berwick:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Standard 8-ton excavator with 5–7 tipper-truck cycles.</strong> Needs 3.5m of side-access width and a stable driveway. Dig completed in 1–2 days. Lowest cost per cubic metre. About 60% of Berwick blocks suit this.</li>
          <li><strong>3-ton mid-size excavator with smaller 7m³ tippers.</strong> Needs about 2.4m of side-access width. Dig in 2–3 days. Modest cost premium ($1,500–$3,000) over the 8-ton option. Common on newer Officer and Clyde North estate blocks with narrower side-access.</li>
          <li><strong>1.7-ton mini-excavator through a 1.2m gate.</strong> For tight Endeavour Hills, narrow-frontage Hampton Park, and any block where access is genuinely restricted. Dig in 4–6 days. $4,000–$8,000 cost premium over the 8-ton option because production rate is so much slower.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          The fourth option, when it makes sense, is removing a panel of fence
          for the duration of the dig — typically the rear-corner side fence —
          to convert a tight-access block into a standard-access block. Cost
          is $500–$1,200 for fence demolition, dig at the cheaper standard rate,
          and reinstate at $1,800–$3,500 depending on the fence type. We work
          this out at the site visit and compare the two paths in writing.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Australian Standards in play during excavation.</h3>
        <p>
          Three standards govern the dig itself. AS 2870 (residential slabs
          and footings) drives the pier schedule based on the soil
          classification. AS 2783 (use of reinforced concrete in swimming
          pools) sets the structural design of the excavation and shell. AS
          1839 (sprayed concrete) governs the shotcrete application that
          follows the dig. We work to all three and the engineering is
          certified before any concrete is poured.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
